Citations
Date:  31/8/1874
Source:  Daily Southern Cross
Author:
Vol / Page:  3
Edition:
Quote:  The flower, stem, and leaves, enclosed in the above letter when I received it, were those of the sporobolus elongatus, in some districts called "ratstail grass," in others "Chilian grass," and probably a dozen or two local names, for all I know to the contrary. It is a native of the province of Auckland, and of late years has been spreading rapidly, in consequence of the extension of agriculture.
Notes:

Date:  11/2/1875
Source:  Daily Southern Cross
Author:
Vol / Page:  1
Edition:
Quote:  .. he believed that where the land was not wanted to go under the plough, the rats-tail grass would thrive.
Notes:

Date:  25/3/1880
Source:  Waikato Times
Author:
Vol / Page:  2
Edition:
Quote:  On such lands as the Rangiriri hills and Komakorau, where clay obtains and little or no soil is seen, the ratstail grass and some of the poas are almost the only grasses that can be grown.
